  <a href="#1" id="1">
   The report represents the latest in a steady three-decade trend of sending heart attack patients home from the hospital after ever shorter stays.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   In the 1950s, doctors often recommended that patients stay in bed for one to two months after a heart attack.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Now, doctors typically keep heart attack patients hospitalized seven to 10 days.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   In their paper, the doctors determined that 80 of the 507 heart attack patients studied were healthy enough to be considered for early discharge.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   The researchers estimated that if 15 percent of all heart attack patients were discharged after three days, the annual saving would be at least $280 million.
  </a>
